We use a dynamic programming approach to solve the problem. We create a 2D array (dp) with dimensions (m+1)x(n+1), where m is the length of string t and n is the length of string s. We iterate through both strings and update the dp array accordingly. If the characters at positions i-1 in t and j-1 in s are equal, we increment the value in the dp array at position (i, j). Finally, we return the value at position (m, n), which will be true if s is a subsequence of t and false otherwise.

The time complexity is O(m*n) because we iterate through both strings once. The space complexity is O(m*n) due to the 2D array. The energy implications are low because the solution is efficient and does not require excessive computational resources.

